{"parse":{"title":"Pupil premium","pageid":45358155,"revid":785654111,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>The <b>pupil premium</b> is a grant given by the government to schools in <a href=\"/wiki/England\" title=\"England\">England</a> to decrease the attainment gap for the most disadvantaged children, whether by income or by family upheaval. For each pupil who is eligible for <a href=\"/wiki/Free_school_meal\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Free school meal\">free school meals</a>, their school receives \u00a31,320 (if a primary school) or \u00a3935 (if a secondary school).<sup id=\"cite_ref-govuk_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-govuk-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Schools receive an extra premium of \u00a31,900 for pupils:\n</p>\n<ul><li>in local authority care</li>\n<li>adopted from care (and the parent self-declares)</li>\n<li>were in care in the last year, which ceased by virtue of a special guardianship order (and the guardian self-declares),<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> residence order or <a href=\"/wiki/Child_Arrangement_Order\" title=\"Child Arrangement Order\">Child Arrangement Order</a>.</li></ul>\n<p>Service children also receive an allocation of \u00a3300, if a parent is serving in the armed forces or is in receipt of a service pension.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>The pupil premium was introduced in 2011 by the <a href=\"/wiki/Cameron%E2%80%93Clegg_coalition\" title=\"Cameron\u2013Clegg coalition\">Conservative\u2014Liberal Democrat coalition government</a> at \u00a3488 per pupil. It increased to \u00a3600 per pupil in 2012\u201313 and eligibility was extended to pupils who have been eligible for free school meals at any point in the last six years (known as the 'Ever 6' Free School Meals measure).<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Audit\">Audit</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Pupil_premium&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Audit\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Schools in receipt of the pupil premium grant are required to account for its use and report this on their websites,<sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> and with specific reference to how it is used to help disadvantaged pupils, as part of the <a href=\"/wiki/OFSTED\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"OFSTED\">OFSTED</a> inspection framework.<sup id=\"cite_ref-govuk_1-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-govuk-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> Ofsted will recommend that a school should conduct an independent pupil premium review if, as a result of a section 5 inspection, it has identified specific issues regarding the provision for disadvantaged pupils.<sup id=\"cite_ref-govuk_review_6-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-govuk_review-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Effectiveness\">Effectiveness</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Pupil_premium&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Effectiveness\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The <a href=\"/wiki/Department_for_Education\" title=\"Department for Education\">Department for Education</a> published an evaluation of the introduction of the pupil premium by the <a href=\"/wiki/University_of_Manchester\" title=\"University of Manchester\">University of Manchester</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Newcastle_University\" title=\"Newcastle University\">Newcastle University</a> in 2013 which reviewed how schools were identifying and targeting disadvantaged pupils for support.<sup id=\"cite_ref-7\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>The think tank <a href=\"/wiki/Demos_(UK_think_tank)\" title=\"Demos (UK think tank)\">Demos</a> published an analysis in January 2015.  They claim that, since 2011, for free school meals-eligible pupils, whose number has grown significantly, the attainment gap has widened, whereas it has narrowed for those in local authority care. It noted the number of free school meal-eligible pupils who achieved 5 GCSEs (including English and Mathematics) at grades A*-C was 33.7%, compared to 60.7% for non-eligible students (as at the first-round Summer 2014 results); with lower relative attainment by 27 percent of such students.  It added the gap widened by 0.3% since 2013.<sup id=\"cite_ref-tes_8-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-tes-8\">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup> This follows a similar widening in its previous report. However it noted in the same period overall attainment has increased significantly.<sup id=\"cite_ref-guardian_9-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-guardian-9\">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>The <a href=\"/wiki/Department_for_Education\" title=\"Department for Education\">Department for Education</a> has disputed Demos' analysis, its spokesman stating: \"It is nonsense to say that the attainment gap is widening. The 2014 results \u2013 when analysed with our more informative and accurate measure \u2013 show the gap has narrowed by almost 4 per cent since 2012, the year after the pupil premium was introduced.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-tes_8-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-tes-8\">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup> The <a href=\"/wiki/Sutton_Trust\" title=\"Sutton Trust\">Sutton Trust</a> reviewed the impact of the introduction of the pupil premium in 2015.<sup id=\"cite_ref-10\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-10\">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Pupil_premium&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-govuk-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-govuk_1-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-govuk_1-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\"> <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/pupil-premium-conditions-of-grant-2016-to-2017/pupil-premium-2016-to-2017-conditions-of-grant#rates-for-eligible-pupils\">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/pupil-premium-conditions-of-grant-2016-to-2017/pupil-premium-2016-to-2017-conditions-of-grant#rates-for-eligible-pupils</a><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">23 February</span> 2017</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.gov.uk%2Fgovernment%2Fpublications%2Fpupil-premium-conditions-of-grant-2016-to-2017%2Fpupil-premium-2016-to-2017-conditions-of-grant%23rates-for-eligible-pupils&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3APupil+premium\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span> <span style=\"font-size:100%\" class=\"error citation-comment\">Missing or empty <code style=\"color:inherit; border:inherit; padding:inherit;\">&#124;title=</code> (<a href=\"/wiki/Help:CS1_errors#citation_missing_title\" title=\"Help:CS1 errors\">help</a>)</span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www2.schoolcircular.co.uk/lib/attachments/Appendi